China cut its benchmark lending rates for corporate and household loans for a second straight month at its January fixing on Thursday, while lowering a mortgage reference rate for the first time in nearly two years. The one-year loan prime rate (LPR) was lowered by 10 basis points to 3.70 percent from 3.80 percent and the five-year LPR was reduced by five basis points to 4.60 percent from 4.65 percent. In December last year, the People's Bank of China (PBOC) cut the one-year LPR for the first time since April from 3.85 percent to 3.80 percent. The cut to the five-year LPR on Thursday was the first reduction since April 2020. The central bank cut the five-year LPR because the economy is currently facing downward pressure, and cutting the rate at the beginning of the year reflects the country's economic policy direction of stabilizing economic growth, lowering financing costs and increasing currency liquidity during 2022, said Yan Yuejin, research director E-House China R&D Institute, in a Securities Times report. The five-year LPR cut will also ease pressure on China's real estate market, said Li Yujia in the same report, Li is the chief researcher at the Guangdong Housing Policy Research Center. The rate cut is expected to lower borrowing costs and encourage more buyers into the property market, in turn helping real estate developers with their cash flow, and ensuring housing delivery. Li further predicted that if the slump in the property market continues this month, the central bank may continue to lower LPR. The cut to the five-year LPR was the first reduction since April 2020. LPR affects the lending rates for corporate and household loans in the country. All 43 participants in a snap poll by ReutersÂ predicted a cut to the one-year LPR for a second straight month. Among them, 40 respondents also forecast a reduction in the five-year LPR rate. Most new and outstanding loans in China are based on the one-year LPR. The five-year rate influences the pricing of mortgages. (With input from Reuters)